ician)|Scott Walker]] and Lieutenant Governor [[Rebecca Kleefisch]], first elected in 2010, sought re-election to a second term after surviving a [[Wisconsin gubernatorial recall election|recall election]] in 2012. \n\nThe Democratic Party nominated business executive [[Mary Burke]] and state senator [[John Lehman (Wisconsin politician)|John Lehman]] for Governor and Lieutenant Governor, respectively.  Burke was a member of the [[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]] school board and former [[Wisconsin Department of Commerce|Secretary of Wisconsin's Department of Commerce]].  Lehman was a state senator and former teacher from [[Racine, Wisconsin|Racine]], who had just won back his senate seat in a [[2012 Wisconsin Senate recall elections|recall election]].\n\nWalker and Kleefisch won the November election with 52% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://archive.jsonline.com/news/statepolitics/walkers-burkes-political-futures-hang-in-balance-with-vote-b99382151z1-281512301.html/|title= Walker defeats Burke for 3rd victory in 4 years |newspaper= [[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] |date= November 5, 2014 |last= Stein |first= Jason |accessdate= April 19, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin | title=2014 Wisconsin gubernatorial election<ref name=\"wecgen\">{{cite report|url= https://elections.wi.gov/sites/elections.wi.gov/files/11.4.14%20Summary%20Results-all%20offices.pdf |title= Canvass Results for 2014 General Election - 11/4/2014|date= November 26, 2014 |accessdate= April 20, 2020 |publisher= [[Wisconsin Elections Commission]]}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link |\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]] (incumbent) /<br />[[Rebecca Kleefisch]] (incumbent)\n  |votes      = 1,259,706\n  |percentage = 52.26%\n  |change     = -0.79%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link |\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Mary Burke]] /<br />[[John Lehman (Wisconsin politician)|John Lehman]]\n  |votes      = 1,122,913\n  |percentage = 46.59%\n  |change     = +0.31%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Libertarian Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Robert Burke /<br />Joseph M. Brost\n  |votes      = 18,720\n  |percentage = 0.78%\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Independent (United States)\n  |candidate  = Dennis Fehr\n  |votes      = 7,530\n  |percentage = 0.31%\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = \n  |candidate  = ''Scattering''\n  |votes      = 1,445\n  |percentage = 0.06%\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box plurality |\n  |votes      = 136,793\n  |percentage = 5.68%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box total |\n  |votes      = 2,410,314\n  |percentage = 100.0%\n  |change     = -4.20%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Attorney General===\nRepublican incumbent Attorney General [[J. B. Van Hollen]], first elected in 2006, did not seek re-election to a third term.  [[Waukesha County, Wisconsin|Waukesha County]] District Attorney [[Brad Schimel]] defeated [[Jefferson County, Wisconsin|Jefferson County]] District Attorney Susan Happ in the November general election.\n\n====Republican primary====\n*[[Brad Schimel]], [[Waukesha County, Wisconsin|Waukesha County]] District Attorney, ran unopposed for the Republican nomination.\n\n====Democratic primary====\n=====Candidates=====\n*Susan Happ, [[Jefferson County, Wisconsin|Jefferson County]] District Attorney\n*[[Jon Richards]], State Representative\n*Ismael Ozanne, [[Dane County, Wisconsin|Dane County]] District Attorney\n\n=====Endorsements=====\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Susan Happ\n| list =\n;County District Attorneys\n* Frederick Bourg, [[Bayfield County, Wisconsin|Bayfield County]]\n* Angela Barenek, [[Barron County, Wisconsin|Barron County]]\n* Gary King, [[Eau Claire County, Wisconsin|Eau Claire County]]\n* Chuck Simono, [[Forest County, Wisconsin|Forest County]]\n* Mark Fuhr, [[Price County, Wisconsin|Price County]]\n* Louis Molepski, Jr., [[Portage County, Wisconsin|Portage County]]\n* Taavi McMahon, [[Trempealeau County, Wisconsin|Trempealeau County]]\n}}\n\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Ismael Ozanne\n| list =\n;Statewide politicians\n* [[Peg Lautenschlager]], former Wisconsin Attorney General\n* [[Vel Phillips]], former Wisconsin Secretary of State\n;County District Attorneys\n* Larry Nelson, [[Iowa County, Wisconsin|Iowa County]]\n* Kate Findley, [[Lafayette County, Wisconsin|Lafayette County]]\n* Joe DeCecco, [[Sheboygan County, Wisconsin|Sheboygan County]]\n* Kristi Tlusty, [[Taylor County, Wisconsin|Taylor County]]\n;Local politicians\n* [[Joe Parisi]], Dane County Executive\n* Dave Mahoney, Dane County Sheriff\n* Carlo Esqueda, Dane County Clerk of Courts\n* Bob Spoden, [[Rock County, Wisconsin|Rock County]] Sheriff\n* Shawn Pfaff, [[Fitchburg, Wisconsin|Fitchburg]] Mayor\n}}\n\n=====Results=====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Democratic primary results<ref name=primaryresults>{{cite web|url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/statepolitics/wisconsin-2014-fall-primary-election-results-253583691.html |title=Wisconsin 2014 fall primary election results |publisher=Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Susan Happ\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 144,367\n| percentage = 52.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Jon Richards\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 90,101\n| percentage = 32.5\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Ismael Ozanne\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 42,555\n| percentage = 15.4\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 277,023\n| percentage= 100\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n====General election====\n=====Candidates=====\n*[[Brad Schimel]], Waukesha County District Attorney 