{"title_page": "Queer Student Cultural Center", "text_new": "The '''Queer Student Cultural Center''' is the current incarnation of the [[coming out]], [[gay]], [[lesbian]], [[bisexual]], [[transgender]], [[genderqueer]], [[intersex]], and allied communities organization of the [[University of Minnesota system|University of Minnesota]] campuses that has been active since May 1969 (under various names).<ref name=washpost>{{cite news |title=Minn. U. Recognizes Club for Homosexuals |work=[[The Washington Post]] |first=Austin |last=Wehrwein |date=1969-11-25 }}</ref>  \n\n== History ==\n\nUpon its creation, QSCC was named \"The Association of GLBT Student Organizations and Their Friends\" upon its inception in 1994 at the U of MN. The group was created by Dave McPartlin and founded by the President of the University Gay\nCommunity (Dave McPartlin), the co-presidents of the University Bisexual Community (Jage Miller and Jonas Duca) and a co-facilitator of the University Lesbians (Susanna de Campos Salles) overseen by adviser Doug Halverson. The group was later renamed The Queer Student Cultural Center in 1998.\n\nApproved by the Minnesota Student Association and then University President, Nils Hasselmo, and Vice-President of Student Affairs, Marvalene Hughes, the Association was one of the earlier student groups to get University funding to combat homophobia and tackle issues specific to LGBT students. The group was created to become a 'cultural center' but did not take the name until several years afterwards for fear that inclusion of the word 'culture' would prevent them from security minority status and University status<ref name=conv>{{cite news |title=Personal conversations with Dave, Jage, Jonas and Suzanna |date=1994-02-14}}</ref>{{Verify source|date=August 2010}}.\n\nThe University Bi Community formed as an offshoot of the University Gay Community by Dave McPartlin in 1991, along with the University People of Color and University International Students as a way to reach the growing needs of the student population. Co-chaired leadership of the University Bi Community was taken on by Jage Miller and Jonas Ducat immediately after its inception.\n\nIn 1982, the University Gay Community and University Lesbians were formed as two separate groups from their predecessor group entitled \"Fight Repression of Erotic Expression (FREE), founded by Koreen Phelps and Stephen Ihrig on May 18, 1969. This group began after the duo started teaching a free University course on the West Bank on The Homosexual Revolution, causing it to become the first queer student group in America.\n\nIn 1971, an original officer of FREE, [[Jack Baker (activist)|Jack Baker]], was the first openly gay man elected student body president at a major university. By winning this election he became the first openly gay man to win any public office in the U.S. In 1970, Jack Baker and Mike McConnell also became the first gay couple to seek legal marriage and were featured in Life magazine.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,943880,00.html] Time magazine, ''Adopting a Lover'', Sep 06, 1971</ref> Jack was also re-elected in 1972.\n\n== Important Influences ==\nQSCC/ULGC/FREE has helped accomplish many historically important things for the LGBT community including:\n\n* Electing the first openly gay student body president, [[Jack Baker (activist)|Jack Baker]] in 1970\n* Challenging the homophobia of the student body president in 1989 and requesting his removal.<ref name=mdaily1061989>{{cite news |title=Bergson silent as students call him homophobic, hated |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1989-10-06}}</ref><ref name=eq10251989>{{cite news |title=Impeachment possible for Bergson |work=[[Equal Times]] |date=1989-11-02}}</ref>\n* Spearheading the removal of [[ROTC]] on campus  <ref name=mdaily10101989>{{cite news |title=Student group targets ROTC policy |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1989-10-10}}</ref><ref name=mdaily05041989>{{cite news |title=Hasselmo decries anti-gay practice |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1990-05-04}}</ref> in 1989\n* First lesbian student body president, [[Suzanne Denevan]], elected <ref name=mdaily06251989>{{cite news |title=Denevan: U must fight ROTC homosexual ban |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1990-06-25}}</ref> in 1990\n* National recognition by sports department of 'Gay Day' <ref name=eq0831990>{{cite news |title=UM football designates Oct. 134 \"University Gay Community Day\" |work=[[Equal Times]]|date=1990-08-31}}</ref><ref name=gaze08231990>{{cite news |title='U' Homecoming to be 'University Gay Community Day' for Students, Alumni |work=[[Twin Cities Gaze]] |date=1990-08-23}}</ref><ref name=gaze11091990>{{cite news |title=Homocoming at the dome |work=[[Equal Times]] |date=1990-11-09}}</ref> in 1990\n* University recognition of LGBT needs by granting office space and funding<ref name=mdaily10101990>{{cite news |title=U gay, lesbian community asks for space in Coffman |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1990-10-10}}</ref><ref name=mdaily11291990>{{cite news |title=McPartlin/UGC Gets Office Space for U Gays/Lesbians/Bi's |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1990-11-29}}</ref><ref name=mdaily03251991>{{cite news |title=Gay/bi/lesbian group to receive funding |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1991-03-25}}</ref> in 1990\n\n== Names over the years ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2010}}\n* 1969: Fight Repression of Erotic Expression (FREE).\n* 1972: Minnesota Gay Activists.\n* 1973: University Community Gay Association.\n* 1977: Minnesota Lesbian Gay Community.\n* 1982: separated into University Lesbians and University Gay Community.\n* 1991: Association of Gay/Lesbian/Bisexual Student Organizations and Their Friends (AGLBSOTF) formed from the groups:\n** University Gay Community.\n** University Lesbians.\n** University Bisexual Community.\n** Delta Lambda Phi Fraternity.\n** GLBT International Students.\n** GLB Medical Students.\n** GLBT Students of Color.\n** Heterosexuals Unafraid of Gays (HUGS).\n*1998: Queer Student Cultural Center (QSCC).\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LGBT}}\n*[[List of LGBT community centers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Refbegin}}\n* Swan, Wallace. (2004). ''Handbook of Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual, and Transgender Administration and Policy''. CRC Press. p.&nbsp;261. {{ISBN|0-8247-4791-7}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|title=Out of Silence: FREE, Minnesota's First Gay Rights Organization|last1=Johansen|first1=Bruce|journal=[[Minnesota History (journal)|Minnesota History]]|volume=66|issue=5|pages=186\u2013201|jstor=26608837|url=https://web.archive.org/save/http://collections.mnhs.org/MNHistoryMagazine/articles/66/v66i05p186-201.pdf|date=2019}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.qscc.org/ Queer Student Cultural Center]\n* [http://www.glbta.umn.edu/ University of Minnesota GLBTA Programs Office]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050102211326/http://www.mndaily.com/articles/2004/03/22/8812 Minnesota Daily story on funding cut in 2004]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070824125433/http://notes.hillel.org/hillel/exchange.nsf/4631b84b253300e4852568da00675ff6/07086D1B2ADE24ED85256FD4007926EC?OpenDocument \"Hillel Homepage\" Who is he? He is she. Me is who: Lessons from Transgender Jews] Program presented by Hillel in cooperation with QSCC\n\n[[Category:LGBT youth organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Queer organizations]]\n[[Category:University of Minnesota]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Minnesota]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Queer Student Cultural Center''' is the current incarnation of the [[coming out]], [[gay]], [[lesbian]], [[bisexual]], [[transgender]], [[genderqueer]], [[intersex]], and allied communities organization of the [[University of Minnesota system|University of Minnesota]] campuses that has been active since May 1969 (under various names).<ref name=washpost>{{cite news |title=Minn. U. Recognizes Club for Homosexuals |work=[[The Washington Post]] |first=Austin |last=Wehrwein |date=1969-11-25 }}</ref>  \n\n== History ==\n\nUpon its creation, QSCC was named \"The Association of GLBT Student Organizations and Their Friends\" upon its inception in 1994 at the U of MN. The group was created by Dave McPartlin and founded by the President of the University Gay\nCommunity (Dave McPartlin), the co-presidents of the University Bisexual Community (Jage Miller and Jonas Duca) and a co-facilitator of the University Lesbians (Susanna de Campos Salles) overseen by adviser Doug Halverson. The group was later renamed The Queer Student Cultural Center in 1998.\n\nApproved by the Minnesota Student Association and then University President, Nils Hasselmo, and Vice-President of Student Affairs, Marvalene Hughes, the Association was one of the earlier student groups to get University funding to combat homophobia and tackle issues specific to LGBT students. The group was created to become a 'cultural center' but did not take the name until several years afterwards for fear that inclusion of the word 'culture' would prevent them from security minority status and University status<ref name=conv>{{cite news |title=Personal conversations with Dave, Jage, Jonas and Suzanna |date=1994-02-14}}</ref>{{Verify source|date=August 2010}}.\n\nThe University Bi Community formed as an offshoot of the University Gay Community by Dave McPartlin in 1991, along with the University People of Color and University International Students as a way to reach the growing needs of the student population. Co-chaired leadership of the University Bi Community was taken on by Jage Miller and Jonas Ducat immediately after its inception.\n\nIn 1982, the University Gay Community and University Lesbians were formed as two separate groups from their predecessor group entitled \"Fight Repression of Erotic Expression (FREE), founded by Koreen Phelps and Stephen Ihrig on May 18, 1969. This group began after the duo started teaching a free University course on the West Bank on The Homosexual Revolution, causing it to become the first queer student group in America.\n\nIn 1971, an original officer of FREE, [[Jack Baker (activist)|Jack Baker]], was the first openly gay man elected student body president at a major university. By winning this election he became the first openly gay man to win any public office in the U.S. In 1970, Jack Baker and Mike McConnell also became the first gay couple to seek legal marriage and were featured in Life magazine.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,943880,00.html] Time magazine, ''Adopting a Lover'', Sep 06, 1971</ref> Jack was also re-elected in 1972.\n\n== Important Influences ==\nQSCC/ULGC/FREE has helped accomplish many historically important things for the LGBT community including:\n\n* Electing the first openly gay Student Body President, [[Jack Baker (activist)|Jack Baker]] in 1970\n* Challenging the homophobia of the student body president in 1989 and requesting his removal.<ref name=mdaily1061989>{{cite news |title=Bergson silent as students call him homophobic, hated |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1989-10-06}}</ref><ref name=eq10251989>{{cite news |title=Impeachment possible for Bergson |work=[[Equal Times]] |date=1989-11-02}}</ref>\n* Spearheading the removal of [[ROTC]] on campus  <ref name=mdaily10101989>{{cite news |title=Student group targets ROTC policy |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1989-10-10}}</ref><ref name=mdaily05041989>{{cite news |title=Hasselmo decries anti-gay practice |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1990-05-04}}</ref> in 1989\n* First Lesbian Student Body President, [[Suzanne Denevan]], elected <ref name=mdaily06251989>{{cite news |title=Denevan: U must fight ROTC homosexual ban |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1990-06-25}}</ref> in 1990\n* National recognition by sports department of 'Gay Day' <ref name=eq0831990>{{cite news |title=UM football designates Oct. 134 \"University Gay Community Day\" |work=[[Equal Times]]|date=1990-08-31}}</ref><ref name=gaze08231990>{{cite news |title='U' Homecoming to be 'University Gay Community Day' for Students, Alumni |work=[[Twin Cities Gaze]] |date=1990-08-23}}</ref><ref name=gaze11091990>{{cite news |title=Homocoming at the dome |work=[[Equal Times]] |date=1990-11-09}}</ref> in 1990\n* University recognition of LGBT needs by granting office space and funding<ref name=mdaily10101990>{{cite news |title=U gay, lesbian community asks for space in Coffman |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1990-10-10}}</ref><ref name=mdaily11291990>{{cite news |title=McPartlin/UGC Gets Office Space for U Gays/Lesbians/Bi's |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1990-11-29}}</ref><ref name=mdaily03251991>{{cite news |title=Gay/bi/lesbian group to receive funding |work=[[The Minnesota Daily]] |date=1991-03-25}}</ref> in 1990\n\n== Names over the years ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2010}}\n* 1969: Fight Repression of Erotic Expression (FREE).\n* 1972: Minnesota Gay Activists.\n* 1973: University Community Gay Association.\n* 1977: Minnesota Lesbian Gay Community.\n* 1982: separated into University Lesbians and University Gay Community.\n* 1991: Association of Gay/Lesbian/Bisexual Student Organizations and Their Friends (AGLBSOTF) formed from the groups:\n** University Gay Community.\n** University Lesbians.\n** University Bisexual Community.\n** Delta Lambda Phi Fraternity.\n** GLBT International Students.\n** GLB Medical Students.\n** GLBT Students of Color.\n** Heterosexuals Unafraid of Gays (HUGS).\n*1998: Queer Student Cultural Center (QSCC).\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LGBT}}\n*[[List of LGBT community centers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Refbegin}}\n* Swan, Wallace. (2004). ''Handbook of Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual, and Transgender Administration and Policy''. CRC Press. p.&nbsp;261. {{ISBN|0-8247-4791-7}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|title=Out of Silence: FREE, Minnesota's First Gay Rights Organization|last1=Johansen|first1=Bruce|journal=[[Minnesota History (journal)|Minnesota History]]|volume=66|issue=5|pages=186\u2013201|jstor=26608837|url=https://web.archive.org/save/http://collections.mnhs.org/MNHistoryMagazine/articles/66/v66i05p186-201.pdf|date=2019}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.qscc.org/ Queer Student Cultural Center]\n* [http://www.glbta.umn.edu/ University of Minnesota GLBTA Programs Office]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050102211326/http://www.mndaily.com/articles/2004/03/22/8812 Minnesota Daily story on funding cut in 2004]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070824125433/http://notes.hillel.org/hillel/exchange.nsf/4631b84b253300e4852568da00675ff6/07086D1B2ADE24ED85256FD4007926EC?OpenDocument \"Hillel Homepage\" Who is he? He is she. Me is who: Lessons from Transgender Jews] Program presented by Hillel in cooperation with QSCC\n\n[[Category:LGBT youth organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Queer organizations]]\n[[Category:University of Minnesota]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Minnesota]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queer_Student_Cultural_Center"}
{"title_page": "Eddie Alderson", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Eddie Alderson\n|image       = \n|caption     = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1994|10|27}}\n|birth_place = {{nowrap|[[Bucks County, Pennsylvania]], U.S.}}\n|occupation  = Actor\n|yearsactive = 2001\u2013present\n|parents     = {{unbulleted list|Richard Alderson|Kathy Alderson}}\n|relatives   = [[Kristen Alderson]] (sister)\n}}\n\n'''Eddie Alderson''' (born October 27, 1994) is an [[American actor]], best known for his portrayal of [[Matthew Buchanan]] on the [[ABC Daytime]] [[United States|American]] [[soap opera]] ''[[One Life to Live]]'' in 2001 until 2012.<ref name=\"OR1\">{{cite web|title=Eddie Alderson Bio |url=http://soapoperadigest.com/eddie-alderson-bio |work=[[Soap Opera Digest]] |publisher=[[American Media (publisher)|American Media, Inc.]] |location=United States |accessdate=November 17, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130809145704/http://soapoperadigest.com/eddie-alderson-bio |archivedate=August 9, 2013 |df= }}</ref> Alderson's performance in the role has been met with critical acclaim, having garnered two [[Young Artist Award]] nominations in 2009 and a [[Daytime Emmy Award]] nomination in 2012.\n\n==Early life and career==\nEddie Alderson was born in [[Bucks County, Pennsylvania|Bucks County]], [[Pennsylvania]], to Rich and Kathy Alderson.\n\nAlderson has portrayed Matthew Buchanan on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s  ''One Life to Live'' since May 10, 2001.  He was put on contract with the OLTL series in December 2008.<ref name=\"Contract 2008\">{{cite web |title=''One Life to Live'': Eddie Alderson Lands Contract! |url=http://www.soaps.com/onelifetolive/news/3161/One_Life_to_Live_Eddie_Alderson_Lands_Contract|website=[[Soaps.com]]|publisher=[[SheKnows Media]]|location=United States|date=December 23, 2008|accessdate=December 24, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"SOD 34-01\">{{cite book|chapter=Comings and Goings: Eddie Alderson (Matthew Buchanan)|title=Comings and Goings|work=[[Soap Opera Digest]]|publisher=[[American Media (publisher)|American Media, Inc.]]|location=United States|pages=19|date=January 6, 2009|volume=34|issue=1}}</ref> Alderson's older sister, [[Kristen Alderson]], has portrayed his OLTL friend, [[Starr Manning]], since March 20, 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soaps.com/onelifetolive/actor/244/Kristen_Alderson|title=Kristen Alderson profile - Soaps.com|website=[[Soaps.com]]|publisher=[[SheKnows Media]]|location=United States|accessdate=December 24, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"SC.com Starr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soapcentral.com/oltl/whoswho/starr.php|title=Starr Manning profile - SoapCentral.com|work=[[List of soap opera media outlets|Soapcentral]]|location=United States|accessdate=December 24, 2008}}</ref>\nIn 2007, Alderson appeared with [[Mark Ruffalo]] in ''[[Reservation Road]].''<ref name=\"Reservation Road\"/>  Alderson later played Sanford Clark in the film ''[[Changeling (film)|Changeling]]'' (2008).<ref name=\"Changeling\"/>  He also portrayed the friend of a murdered boy on ''[[Law & Order]]''.\n<ref>[http://soapcentral.com/oltl/news/2011/1110-aldersons.php \"Alderson's moving to LA not Prospect Park\"]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAlderson was diagnosed with [[lymphoma|lymphoma cancer]] in November 2016.<ref name=\"Alderson\">{{cite news|last1=Eades|first1=Chris|title=ONE LIFE TO LIVE Star Eddie Alderson Reveals Cancer Diagnosis|url=http://abc.soapsindepth.com/posts/oltl-one-life-to-live-eddie-alderson-diagnosed-lymphoma-cancer-118915/photos/alderson-family-10-210321|accessdate=November 16, 2016|work=[[ABC Soaps In Depth]]|agency=[[Bauer Media Group]]|date=November 15, 2016|location=United States}}</ref> On April 26, 2017, it was reported by ''[[Soaps in Depth#Magazines|ABC Soaps in Depth]]'' that he finished his first round of [[chemotherapy]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eades|first1=Chris|title=ONE LIFE TO LIVE's Eddie Alderson Finishes His Cancer Treatments!\n|url=http://abc.soapsindepth.com/posts/one-life-to-live-eddie-alderson-final-cancer-treatment-131004/photos/alderson-family-10-210321|accessdate=July 13, 2017|work=[[Soaps in Depth#Magazines|ABC Soaps in Depth]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]|date=April 26, 2017|location=United States|language=en}}</ref> On July 13, 2017, announced through ''ABC Soaps in Depth'', Alderson was back in chemotherapy.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eades|first1=Chris|title=ONE LIFE TO LIVE's Eddie Alderson Shares Update on Cancer Treatment \u2014 \"Nothing Is Getting Me Down.\"|url=http://abc.soapsindepth.com/posts/oltl-one-life-to-live-eddie-alderson-cancer-update-123074/photos/oltl-eddie-alderson-01-210812|accessdate=July 13, 2017|work=[[Soaps in Depth#Magazines|ABC Soaps in Depth]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]|date=July 13, 2017|location=United States|language=en}}</ref>\nHe came out of the closet as homosexual in 2020.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Reservation Road]]''\n| Lucas Arno\n| {{Plain list |\n* [[Drama (film and television)|Drama film]] [[Film director|directed]] by [[Terry George]].<ref name=\"Reservation Road\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/658331/Reservation-Road/full-credits.html|title=Reservation Road|work=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting System]] ([[Time Warner]])|location=[[Atlanta]]|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Reservation-Road-Joaquin-Phoenix/dp/B0010KP360|title=Reservation Road|work=[[Universal Pictures Home Entertainment|Universal Studios Home Entertainment]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|location=[[Los Angeles]]|date=April 8, 2008|accessdate=November 16, 2016|asin=B0010KP360}}</ref>\n* Based on the book of the same title by [[John Burnham Schwartz]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/Reservation-Vintage-Contemporaries-Burnham-Schwartz/dp/0375702733|title=Reservation Road|authorlink=John Burnham Schwartz|first=John Burnham|last=Schwartz|publisher=[[Vintage Books]]|location=[[New York City]]|year=1999|edition=Paperback|isbn=978-0375702730}}</ref>\n}}\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Changeling (film)|Changeling]]''\n| Sanford Clark\n| [[Psychological drama|Psychological drama film]] directed, co-[[Film producer|produced]] and [[Film score|scored]] by [[Clint Eastwood]] and written by [[J. Michael Straczynski]].<ref name=\"Changeling\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/676834/Changeling/full-credits.html|title=Changeling|work=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting System]] ([[Time Warner]])|location=[[Atlanta]]|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2001\u20142012\n| ''[[One Life to Live]]''\n| [[Matthew Buchanan]]\n| {{Plain list |\n* [[Recurring character|Recurring]] \u2014 (2001\u201408)\n* Contract role \u2014 (2008\u201412)\n* Nominated \u2014 [[Daytime Emmy|Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Younger Actor in a Drama Series]]\n* Nominated \u2014 [[Young Artist Award|Young Artist Award for Best Performance in a TV Series - Recurring Young Actor]]\n* Nominated \u2014 [[Young Artist Award|Young Artist Award for Outstanding Young Ensemble in a TV Series]] <small>(shared with [[Kristen Alderson]], [[Camila Banus]], [[Carmen LoPorto]] and [[Austin Williams]])</small>\n}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Law & Order]]''\n| Todd\n| Episode: \"[[Law & Order (season 19)#Episodes|Pledge]]\" (S 19:Ep 10)\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Award\n! scope=\"col\" | Work\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" | Ref\n|-\n|  rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:center\" | <center>2009</center>\n| [[Young Artist Award]]  [[30th Young Artist Awards#Best Perf